9/|title=CBN (7:00 and 11:00 p.m.): The Man Who Loved The Stars |publisher=Wisconsin State Journal| work=TV/Entertainment|page=5C|date=1989-02-20|via=[[Heritage Microfilm, Inc.#NewspaperArchive|NewspaperARCHIVE]]|accessdate=2019-09-01}} {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190901220700/https://newspaperarchive.com/madison-wisconsin-state-journal-feb-20-1989-p-19/|date=2019-09-01}}<br>(2) {{cite web |last=Erikson |first=Hal |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150824175754/https://www.nytimes.com/movies/movie/123937/Benjamin-Banneker-The-Man-Who-Loved-the-Stars/overview|archivedate=2015-08-04|url=https://www.nytimes.com/movies/movie/123937/Benjamin-Banneker-The-Man-Who-Loved-the-Stars/overview|title=Review Summary: Benjamin Banneker: The Man Who Loved the Stars (1989) |work=Movies|publisher=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=2015-08-25|quote=\nOssie Davis stars in this 60-minute TV drama. Davis plays Benjamin Banneker, the self-taught African-American astronomer, surveyor and almanac author. Banneker accomplished all this in the late 18th and early 19th century, a time when most blacks were held in the grip of slavery. The story details Banneker's first few \"free\" years as a farmer, his correspondence with Thomas Jefferson, and his efforts to help fugitive slaves escape. Benjamin Banneker: The Man Who Loved the Stars was first telecast in February of 1989 over the CBN cable service.}}</ref>\n* The Banneker Room, George Howard Building, [[Howard County, Maryland|Howard County]] Government, [[Ellicott City, Maryland]] (County Council meeting room)<ref>{{cite web |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180302184046/https://cc.howardcountymd.gov/LinkClick.aspx?fileticket=i6EW2ecctMI%3D&portalid=0|archivedate=2018-03-02 |url=https://cc.howardcountymd.gov/LinkClick.aspx?fileticket=i6EW2ecctMI%3D&portalid=0|format=PDF|title=County Council Agenda: July 18, 2015 \u2013 September 4, 2015 |work=Howard County Council|location=[[Ellicott City, Maryland]] |publisher=[[Howard County, Maryland]], government|accessdate=2018-11-16|quote=<br>County Council<br>Monday, July 20, 2015<br />Banneker Room<br />George Howard Building, 3430 Court House Drive, Ellicott City, MD}}</ref>\n* The Banneker Room, The Wayside Inn, Ellicott City, Maryland (guest room)<ref>{{cite web |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181231015255/https://www.waysideinnmd.com/rooms/banneker-room/|archivedate=December 31, 2018|url=https://www.waysideinnmd.com/rooms/banneker-room/|title=The Banneker Room |work=The Wayside Inn |location=[[Ellicott City, Maryland]] |publisher=The Wayside Inn |year=2018|accessdate=December 31, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==List and map of coordinates==\n{{GeoGroup}}\n{{reflist|group=a}}\n==See also==\n[[African-American culture]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==References==\n{{refbegin|45em}}\n* {{cite book|last=Bedini |first=Silvio A.|author-link=Silvio Bedini|year=1971|url=https://archive.org/details/lifeofbenjaminba00silv/page/n7|title=The Life of Benjamin Banneker|place=New York |publisher=[[Charles Scribner's Sons|Scribner]] (copyright 1972) (republished by [[Rancho Cordova, California]]: Landmark Enterprises (1984))|isbn=0910845204|oclc=593414330|lccn=78162755|accessdate=2019-08-29|via=[[Internet Archive]]}}\n* {{cite book|last=Bedini|first=Silvio A.|author-link=Silvio Bedini|url=https://archive.org/details/lifeofbenjaminba00bedi/page/n7|year=1999|title=The Life of Benjamin Banneker: The First African-American Man of Science|edition=2nd|location=Baltimore|publisher=Maryland Historical Society|isbn=0-938420-59-3|oclc=894558859|lccn=98022848|accessdate=2019-09-11|via=[[Internet Archive]]}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category-inline|Benjamin Banneker}}<br>\n{{commons category-inline|Benjamin Banneker Historical Park and Museum}}<br>\n{{commons category-inline|Benjamin Banneker Park, Washington, D.C.}}\n\n{{Portal bar|Biography|History|United States|Maryland}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Banneker, Mythology and legacy of Benjamin}}\n[[Category:African-American culture]]\n[[Category:Commemoration]]\n[[Category:Commemorative stamps]]\n[[Category:Community centers in Maryland]]\n[[Category:Community centers in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Legacies by person]]\n[[Category:Monuments and memorials by person]]\n[[Category:National Mall and Memorial Parks]]\n[[Category:Museums in Baltimore County, Maryland]]\n[[Category:Museums in Annapolis, Maryland]]\n[[Category:Parks in Baltimore County, Maryland]]\n[[Category:Parks in Arlington County, Virginia]]\n[[Category:Planetaria in the United States]]\n[[Category:Playgrounds]]\n[[Category:Tributes by person]]\n[[Category:Urban legends]]\n", "name_user": "Corker1", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBenjamin Banneker Historical Park and Museum, Baltimore County, Maryland:add wikilink", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Commemorations_of_Benjamin_Banneker"}
{"title_page": "Nick Denes", "text_new": "{{Infobox college coach\n| name = Nick Denes\n| image = \n| alt = \n| caption = \n| birth_date = {{Birth date|1906|12|16}}\n| birth_place = [[Bucharest|Bucharest, Romania]]\n| death_date = {{Death date and age|1975|11|28|1906|12|16}}\n| death_place = [[Bowling Green, Kentucky]]\n| alma_mater = \n| player_sport1 = \n| player_years2 = \n| player_team2 = \n| player_positions = \n| coach_sport1 = Football\n| coach_years2 = 1927\n| coach_team2 =  Champaign HS (IL) (backfield)\n| coach_years3 = 1929\u20131936\n| coach_team3 = [[Corbin High School|Corbin HS (KY)]]\n| coach_years4 = 1937\u20131938\n| coach_team4 = [[UT Martin Skyhawks football|Tennessee JC]]\n| coach_years5 = 1939\u20131956\n| coach_team5 = [[Louisville Male High School|Louisville Male HS (KY)]]\n| coach_years6 = 1957\u20131967\n| coach_team6 = [[Western Kentucky Hilltoppers football|Western Kentucky]]\n| coach_sport7 = Basketball\n| coach_years8 = 1929\u20131937\n| coach_team8 = [[Corbin High School|Corbin HS (KY)]]\n| coach_sport9 = Baseball\n| coach_years10 = 1958\u20131962\n| coach_team10 = [[Western Kentucky Hilltoppers baseball|Western Kentucky]]\n| overall_record = 57\u201339\u20137 (college football)<br>48\u201340\u20131 (college baseball)\n| bowl_record = 1\u20130\n| tournament_record = \n| championships = Football<br>1 [[Ohio Valley Conference|OVC]] (1963)\n| awards = [[Ohio Valley Conference|OVC]] Coach of the Year (1963)\n| coaching_records = \n}}\n'''Nicholas G. Denes''' (1906 \u2013 November 28, 1975) was an [[American football]], [[basketball]], and [[baseball]] coach.  He served as the head football coach at [[Western Kentucky University]] from 1957 to 1967, compiling a record of 57\u201339\u20137.  His {{cfb link|year=1963|team=Western Kentucky Hilltoppers|title=1963 Western Kentucky Hilltoppers football team}} went undefeated, winning the [[Ohio Valley Conference]] conference title and the [[1963 Tangerine Bowl]]. Denes was also the head baseball coach at Western Kentucky from 1958 to 1962, tallying a mark of  48\u201340\u20131.  [[Nick Denes Field]], the home venue for the [[Western Kentucky Hilltoppers baseball]] team, is named for him.  Denes was the head football coach at the University of Tennessee Junior College\u2014now known as the [[University of Tennessee at Martin]]\u2014from 1937 to 1938.  He coached athletics at [[Corbin High School]] in [[Corbin, Kentucky]] from 1929 to 1937 and at [[Louisville Male High School]] in [[Louisville, Kentucky]] from 1939 to 1957.\n\n==Early life and education==\nDenes was born in 1906 in [[Bucharest|Bucharest, Romania]] and raised in [[Garrett, Indiana]].  He graduated from the [[University of Illinois]] and received a master's degree from the [[University of Kentucky]].<ref name=obituary>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Giant among coaches...Highly successful, but popular Nick Denes dies at 69 |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/23842874/the_courierjournal/ |newspaper=[[The Courier-Journal]] |location=[[Louisville, Kentucky]] |date=November 30, 1975 |page=C1 |access-date=September 18, 2018 |via=[[Newspapers.com]] {{Open access}} }}</ref>\n\n==Coaching career==\nDenes began his coaching career in 1927, as a backfield coach for the football team at Champaign High School in [[Champaign, Illinois]].  In 1929 he was hired as head football and head basketball coach at [[Corbin High School]] in [[Corbin, Kentucky]].  His football teams compiled a record of 63\u201311\u20135 in eight seasons.  They were champions of the Cumberland Valley Conference four times (1931, 1933\u20131935) and runners-up twice (1930, 1932).  His basketball teams were 142\u201339 and won the Cumberland Valley Conference four times (1929, 1931, 1932, 1936).<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=N. G. Denes at Univ. Of Tenn. Junior College\u2014Made Enviable Record at Corbin, Ky. |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/23843546/garrett_clipper/ |newspaper=Garrett Clipper |location=[[Garrett, Indiana]] |date=September 13, 1937 |page=1 |access-date=September 18, 2018 |via=[[Newspapers.com]] {{Open access}} }}</ref>\n\n==Death==\nDenes died on November 28, 1975, at Greenview Hospital in [[Bowling Green, Kentucky]].<ref name=obituary/>\n\n==Head coaching record==\n===College football===\n{{CFB Yearly Record Start | type = coach | team = | conf = | bowl = | poll = no }}\n{{CFB Yearly Record Subhead\n | name      = [[Western Kentucky Hilltoppers football|Western Kentucky Hilltoppers]]\n | conf      = [[Ohio Valley Conference]]\n | startyear = 1957\n | endyear   = 1967\n}}\n{{CFB Yearly Record Entry\n | year         = [[1957 NCAA College Division football season|1957]]\n | name         = Western Kentucky\n | overall      = 5\u20133\u20131\n | conference   = 1\u20133\u20131\n | confstanding = T\u20134th\n | bowlname     = \n | bowloutcome  = \n | bcsbowl      = \n | ranking      = no\n | ranking2     = no\n}}\n{{CFB Yearly Record Entry\n | championship = \n | year         = [[1958 NCAA College Division football season|1958]]\n | name         = Western Kentucky\n | overall      = 4\u20135\n | conference   = 2\u20134\n | confstanding = T\u20135th\n | bowlname     = \n | bowloutcome  = \n | bcsbowl      = \n | ranking      = no\n | ranking2     = no\n}}\n{{CFB Yearly Record Entry\n | championship = \n | year         = [[1959 NCAA College Division football season|1959]]\n | name         = Western Kentucky\n | overall      = 5\u20134\n | conference   = 3\u20133\n | confstanding = 4th\n | bowlname     = \n | bowloutcome  = \n | bcsbowl      = \n | ranking      = no\n | ranking2     = no\n}}\n{{CFB Yearly Record Entry\n | championship = \n | year         = [[1960 NCAA College Division football season|1960]]\n | name         = Western Kentucky\n | overall      = 2\u20136\u20131\n | conference   = 1\u20134\u20131\n | confstanding = T\u20136th\n | bowlname     = \n | bowloutcome  = \n | bcsbowl      = \n | ranking      = no\n | ranking2     = no\n}}\n{{CFB Yearly Record Entry\n | championship = \n | year         = [[1961 NCAA College Division football season|1961]]\n | name         = Western Kentucky\n | overall      = 6\u20133\n | conference   = 4\u20132\n | confstanding = 3rd\n | bowlname     = \n | bowloutcome  = \n | bcsbowl      = \n | ranking      = no\n | ranking2     = no\n}}\n{{CFB Yearly Record Entry\n | championship = \n | year         = [[1962 NCAA College Division football season|1962]]\n | name         = Western Kentucky\n | overall      = 5\u20133\n | conference   = 3\u20133\n | confstanding = 5th\n | bowlname     = \n | bowloutcome  = \n | bcsbowl      = \n | ranking      = no\n | ranking2     = no\n}}\n{{CFB Yearly Record Entry\n | championship = conference\n | year         = [[1963 NCAA College Division football season|1963]]\n | name         = [[1963 Western Kentucky Hilltoppers football team|Western Kentucky]]\n | overall      = 10\u20130\u20131\n | conference   = 7\u20130\n | confstanding = 1st\n | bowlname     = [[1963 Tangerine Bowl|Tangerine]]\n | bowloutcome  = W\n | bcsbowl      = \n | ranking      = no\n | ranking2     = no\n}}\n{{CFB Yearly Record Entry\n | championship = \n | year         = [[1964 NCAA College Division football season|1964]]\n | name         = Western Kentucky\n | overall      = 6\u20133\u20131\n | conference   = 3\u20133\u20131\n | confstanding = T\u20133rd\n | bowlname     = \n | bowloutcome  = \n | bcsbowl      = \n | ranking      = no\n | ranking2     = no\n}}\n{{CFB Yearly Record Entry\n | championship = \n | year         = [[1965 NCAA College Division football season|1965]]\n | name         = Western Kentucky\n | overall      = 2\u20136\u20132\n | conference   = 1\u20135\u20131\n | confstanding = 7th\n | bowlname     = \n | bowloutcome  = \n | bcsbowl      = \n | ranking      = no\n | ranking2     = no\n}}\n{{CFB Yearly Record Entry\n | championship = \n | year         = [[1966 NCAA College Division football season|1966]]\n | name  